label.value: cell cycle arrest at mitotic G2/M phase transition during stationary phase

value.value: A cellular process phenotype in which progression through the mitotic cell cycle is arrested at the mitotic G2/M phase transition when the population in which the cell is found is in stationary phase.

label.value: decreased cell population growth on raffinose carbon source

value.value: A vegetative cell population growth phenotype in which cell growth is decreased relative to normal under aerobic conditions and in a medium containing raffinose as the carbon source.

definition.value: Note that cell growth terms refer to growth under aerobic conditions unless stated otherwise.

label.value: normal growth on glucose carbon source

value.value: A vegetative cell population growth phenotype in which cells grow normally (i.e. indistinguishably from wild type) in a medium containing glucose as the carbon source.

A cell phenotype observed in the vegetative growth phase of the life cycle in which a cell that is exposed to anaerobic conditions fails to grow upon being returned to aerobic conditions, and eventually dies.

definition.value: Note that if you have done an experiment that assays the viability of a population of cells, such as looking at colony growth or growth in liquid culture, you should also annotate to 'inviable cell population' (FYPO:0002059) or one of its descendants.

label.value: normal growth on fructose carbon source

value.value: A vegetative cell population growth phenotype in which cells grow normally (i.e. indistinguishably from wild type) in a medium containing fructose as the carbon source.
A molecular function phenotype in which the observed rate of ATPase activity is abnormal.
A molecular function phenotype in which the observed rate of ATPase activity is decreased.
A cellular process phenotype observed in the vegetative growth phase of the life cycle in which proton (H+) transport is normal (i.e. indistinguishable from wild type).

label.value: decreased methionine import during nitrogen starvation

value.value: A cellular process phenotype in which the import of methionine into the cell occurs to a lower extent than normal when the cell is subject to nitrogen starvation.

definition.value: This term can be used for any circumstances in which cells are starved for nitrogen. Note that cells may enter G0 (quiescence) when subjected to prolonged nitrogen starvation; this term is not restricted to G0.

value.value: A cell phenotype observed in the vegetative growth phase of the life cycle in which the measured intracellular pH is lower than normal.

A cellular process phenotype observed in the vegetative growth phase of the life cycle in which hypermethylation of the 7-(mono)methylguanosine (m(7)G) cap structure at the 2' position of the guanosine residue to form a 2,2,7-trimethylguanosine cap structure is abnormal.

A cellular process phenotype observed in the vegetative growth phase of the life cycle in which hypermethylation of the 7-(mono)methylguanosine (m(7)G) cap structure at the 2' position of the guanosine residue to form a 2,2,7-trimethylguanosine cap structure is abolished.

label.value: normal growth on sucrose carbon source

value.value: A vegetative cell population growth phenotype in which cells grow normally (i.e. indistinguishably from wild type) in a medium containing sucrose as the carbon source.

label.value: normal growth on maltose carbon source

value.value: A vegetative cell population growth phenotype in which cells grow normally (i.e. indistinguishably from wild type) in a medium containing maltose as the carbon source.

label.value: decreased cell population growth on sucrose carbon source

value.value: A vegetative cell population growth phenotype in which cell growth is decreased relative to normal in a medium containing sucrose as the carbon source.

definition.value: Note that cell growth terms refer to growth under aerobic conditions unless stated otherwise.

label.value: decreased cell population growth on trehalose carbon source

value.value: A vegetative cell population growth phenotype in which cell growth is decreased relative to normal in a medium containing trehalose as the carbon source.

definition.value: Note that cell growth terms refer to growth under aerobic conditions unless stated otherwise.

label.value: loss of viability upon nitrogen starvation

value.value: A cell population phenotype in which a smaller than normal proportion of cells in the population remains viable when cells in a culture in stationary phase are deprived of nitrogen.

definition.value: Use this term to annotate experiments in which a culture is grown under nitrogen-depleted conditions, and then the number of cells viable enough to form a colony upon return to conditions supporting vegetative growth is measured and compared to wild type. Also consider 'sensitive to nitrogen starvation' (FYPO:0002124).

label.value: abolished protein localization during vegetative growth

value.value: A cell phenotype in which a protein does not localize to, and is therefore absent from, a place where it is normally found in the vegetative growth phase of the life cycle.

definition.value: We recommend using one of the more specific terms instead of annotating to this term directly, if possible. If this term is used, we recommend noting which protein(s) were used in the assay.

value.value: A molecular function phenotype in which the observed rate of maltose alpha-glucosidase (also known as maltase) activity is normal (i.e. indistinguishable from wild type).
A molecular function phenotype in which the observed rate of an alpha-glucosidase activity is normal (i.e. indistinguishable from wild type).
A molecular function phenotype in which the observed rate of an alpha-glucosidase activity is abnormal.
A molecular function phenotype in which the observed rate of maltose alpha-glucosidase (also known as maltase) activity is abnormal.
A molecular function phenotype in which the observed rate of an alpha-glucosidase activity is decreased.
A molecular function phenotype in which the observed rate of maltose alpha-glucosidase (also known as maltase) activity is decreased.

label.value: decreased cell density in stationary phase

value.value: A cell population phenotype in which a population reaches stationary phase at, and maintains, a lower cell density than wild type.

A phenotype observed in the vegetative growth phase of the life cycle in which cells show increased sensitivity to Calcofluor White. Cells stop growing (and may die) at a concentration of Calcofluor White that allows wild type cells to grow.

A phenotype observed in the vegetative growth phase of the life cycle in which cells show increased sensitivity to cilofungin. Cells stop growing (and may die) at a concentration of cilofungin that allows wild type cells to grow.

definition.value: Cilofungin is an echinocandin antibiotic, related to echinocandin B.

value.value: A phenotype observed in the vegetative growth phase of the life cycle in which cells show increased sensitivity to one or more enzymes that degrades cell wall polysaccharides. Cells stop growing (and may die) at a concentration of such enzymes that allows wild type cells to grow.

label.value: normal growth on cell wall-degrading enzymes

value.value: A cell phenotype observed in the vegetative growth phase of the life cycle in which vegetative cell growth is normal (i.e. indistinguishable from wild type) in a medium containing one or more enzymes that degrades cell wall polysaccharides.
A cell phenotype observed in the vegetative growth phase of the life cycle in which the amount of beta-D-glucan measured in the cell is greater than normal.
A cell phenotype observed in the vegetative growth phase of the life cycle in which the amount of galactomannan measured in the cell is lower than normal.
A cell phenotype observed in the vegetative growth phase of the life cycle in which the amount of alpha-D-glucan measured in a cell is normal (i.e. indistinguishable from wild type).
A cell phenotype observed in the vegetative growth phase of the life cycle in which the amount of calcium ion measured in a cell is lower than normal.
A cell phenotype observed in the vegetative growth phase of the life cycle in which the amount of calcium ion measured in a cell is higher than normal.
A cell phenotype observed in the vegetative growth phase of the life cycle in which the amount of calcium ion measured in a cell is normal (i.e. indistinguishable from wild type).

label.value: abnormal cellular response to calcium starvation

value.value: A stress response phenotype observed in the vegetative growth phase of the life cycle in which the response to calcium starvation is abnormal.

definition.value: Use this term if you have assayed the response to calcium starvation at the subcellular or molecular level. If you have assayed growth of cells exposed to calcium starvation in culture, use 'sensitive to calcium starvation' (FYPO:0001201).

value.value: A cell phenotype observed in the vegetative growth phase of the life cycle in which cells show increased sensitivity to calcium ion starvation.

definition.value: Use this term if you have assayed growth of cells exposed to calcium starvation in culture. If you have assayed the response to calcium starvation at the subcellular or molecular level, consider annotating to 'abnormal cellular response to calcium starvation' (FYPO:0001200).

label.value: normal cellular response to calcium starvation

value.value: A cellular response phenotype observed in the vegetative growth phase of the life cycle in which the cellular response to calcium starvation is normal (i.e. indistinguishable from wild type).
A cell population phenotype that reflects increased occurrence of coflocculation. In coflocculation, yeast cells coaggregate with cells of another species, usually bacteria.

definition.value: Note: coflocculation between S. pombe and E. coli is sensitive to mannose but not to glucose or galactose. Plant lectins such as HHA, GNA, NPA, or Concanavalin A (ConA) decrease but do not abolish S. pombe-E. coli coflocculation. Cations have different effects: Li+, Na+, K+, Mg2+ or Mn2+ increase coflocculation, Co2+, Zn2+, and Ca2+ have no effect, and Cu2+ or Hg2+ completely abolish coflocculation.

value.value: A cellular process phenotype in which cells enter mitosis earlier or later than normal, relative to cell size or DNA integrity checkpoint status.
A molecular function phenotype in which alpha-glucosidase activity is absent.
A molecular function phenotype in which maltase activity is absent.

A phenotype observed in the vegetative growth phase of the life cycle in which cells show increased sensitivity to raffinose. Cells stop growing (and may die) at a concentration of raffinose that allows wild type cells to grow.

label.value: substance absent from cell during vegetative growth

value.value: A cell phenotype observed in the vegetative growth phase of the life cycle in which the amount of a specific substance measured in a cell is too low to detect.
A cell phenotype observed in the vegetative growth phase of the life cycle in which the amount of a polysaccharide measured in a cell is too low to detect.

A cell phenotype observed in the vegetative growth phase of the life cycle in which the amount of Glc2Man9GlcNAc2 measured in a cell is too low to detect. Glc2Man9GlcNAc2 is an N-glycan that is involved in post-translational modification of proteins, and consists of a branched ten-membered mannooligosaccharide containing two D-glucose residues, nine D-mannosyl residues and two N-acetylglucosamine residues.

definition.value: Note that these terms treat Man(n)GlcNAc and Man(n)GlcNAc2 as equivalent. The reason is that the GlcNAc2 form is attached to N-linked glycoproteins, but the GlcNAc form is what is usually detected in experiments, following cleavage by endoglycosidase H. For the purposes of observing and interpreting phenotypes, the difference is not significant.

value.value: A cell phenotype observed in the vegetative growth phase of the life cycle in which the amount of Glc3Man9GlcNAc measured in a cell is too low to detect. Glc3Man9GlcNAc2 is an N-glycan that is involved in post-translational modification of proteins, and consists of a branched ten-membered mannooligosaccharide containing three D-glucose residues, nine D-mannosyl residues and two N-acetylglucosamine residues.

definition.value: Note that these terms treat Man(n)GlcNAc and Man(n)GlcNAc2 as equivalent. The reason is that the GlcNAc2 form is attached to N-linked glycoproteins, but the GlcNAc form is what is usually detected in experiments, following cleavage by endoglycosidase H. For the purposes of observing and interpreting phenotypes, the difference is not significant.

value.value: A cell phenotype observed in the vegetative growth phase of the life cycle in which the amount of Glc1Man9GlcNAc2 measured in a cell is lower than normal. Glc1Man9GlcNAc2 is an N-glycan that is involved in post-translational modification of proteins, and consists of a branched ten-membered mannooligosaccharide containing one D-glucose residue, nine D-mannosyl residues and two N-acetylglucosamine residues.

definition.value: Note that these terms treat Man(n)GlcNAc and Man(n)GlcNAc2 as equivalent. The reason is that the GlcNAc2 form is attached to N-linked glycoproteins, but the GlcNAc form is what is usually detected in experiments, following cleavage by endoglycosidase H. For the purposes of observing and interpreting phenotypes, the difference is not significant.

value.value: A cell phenotype observed in the vegetative growth phase of the life cycle in which the amount of Man8GlcNAc2 measured in a cell is higher than normal. Man8GlcNAc2 is any N-glycan that consists of a branched ten-membered mannooligosaccharide containing eight D-mannosyl residues and two N-acetylglucosamine residues.

definition.value: Note that these terms treat Man(n)GlcNAc and Man(n)GlcNAc2 as equivalent. The reason is that the GlcNAc2 form is attached to N-linked glycoproteins, but the GlcNAc form is what is usually detected in experiments, following cleavage by endoglycosidase H. For the purposes of observing and interpreting phenotypes, the difference is not significant.

value.value: A phenotype observed in the vegetative growth phase of the life cycle in which cells show increased sensitivity to potassium chloride. Cells stop growing (and may die) at a concentration of potassium chloride that allows wild type cells to grow.
